Hyundai History
Hyundai models range from the Accent, a small three-door hatchback, to the Veracruz crossover SUV. With starting Hyundai car prices ranging from $10,690 to $28,940, and a 10-year / 100,000-mile warranty, Hyundai produces a quality car at an affordable price.
The Hyundai Motor Company is the eighth-largest and the world's fastest-growing auto maker. In 1968, Hyundai released its first of several Hyundai models: the Cortina. The Hyundai Excel was the first Hyundai car to enter the United States in 1986, and set a record for the most automobiles sold (126,000) in the first year of business in the U.S.
After a record-setting year, Hyundai gained a reputation for poor quality after some cost-cutting measures. Hyundai then heavily invested in the design, quality, and manufacturing and long-term research and added a 10-year / 100,000-mile powertrain warranty which helped sales increase dramatically by 2004. Hyundai is now one of the top 100 most valuable brands worldwide.
TrueCar is an independent service provider that improves the car buying experience by collecting, analyzing, and presenting vehicle data from multiple sources. Although TrueCar provides new car pricing information and other data with respect to most vehicles on the market, TrueCar remains independent and is not affiliated with, sponsored by, or endorsed by Hyundai. All use of Hyundai's trademarks, brands, and logos, including all Hyundai marks displayed here, is purely referential, and such marks are the property of Hyundai. TrueCar makes no claim of ownership in such marks, and no claim of affiliation with Hyundai. TrueCar provides information about Hyundai car prices, but does not sell cars, automobile parts, or automobile repair services.






